<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-499-741  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 499 741.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 7 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>BroadBand Technologies introduces new fiber system. (Fiber LoopAccess)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   BroadBand Technologies, Inc. (marketing).andO;Topic:     New TechniqueFiber OpticsVoice CommunicationsISDN.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>BROADBAND TECHNOLOGIES INTRODUCES NEW FIBER SYSTEM RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK,NORTH CAROLINA, U.S.A., 1990 SEP 7 (NB) -- BroadBand Technologies announcedFiber Loop Access, a fiber optic transport system that lets telephonecompanies deliver voice services today, with a simple upgrade to enhanceddigital services under ISDN standards.andP;  The system is being tested by BellAtlantic, NYNEX and Ameritech, and complies with fiber- in-the-looparchitecture recommendations recently released by Bell CommunicationsResearch.andM;Broadband said FLX is cost competitive with copper-based services, andprovides a platform from which they can offer advanced services such as ISDNand broadband services such as video, in a system compatible with today'stelephone network topology.andP;  It also uses an intelligent, software-definedselection capability to let cable companies offer a broad range of videochannels or data services, reducing the bandwidth required for videotransport.andM;Upgrading the FLX System requires only changing line cards at a remoteterminal and at a subscriber's home or curbside pedestal.andM;The FLX System's standard telephone service capability will be commerciallyavailable in the first quarter of 1991.andP;  The switched digital videocapability will be commercially available in the fourth quarter of 1991.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900907/Press Contact: Salim Bhatia, BroadBandTechnologies Research Triangle Park, 919/544-0015)</TEXT></DOC>